  "title": "Earth",
  "content": "<p><strong>Earth</strong>, also known as <strong>Sol III</strong> or rarely as <strong>Terra</strong>, was until it's destruction the third planet within the Sol system. Located within the Hydian Sector, it was capable of sustaining complex life and was the homeworld of the <strong>Human </strong>species. It had one natural satellite, simply known as \"The Moon\" by the planet's inhabitants, and numerous artficial satellites.</p><h1>Astronomical Information</h1><p>Earth orbited its star, Sol, at a distance of roughly 150 million kilometers. In the classical Human measurement system, this defined one&nbsp;<em>Astronomical Unit</em>&nbsp;(AU). Within the Sol system, it was one of the four inner planets that orbited inside of Sol's asteroid belt.</p><h3>Climate and Geography</h3><p>Earth was a class-A terrestrial planet. Being near the center of Sol's habitable zone, Earth experienced a moderate range of temperatures; at the time of it's destruction the average global surface temperature was 61 °F (16.1 °C).</p><p>Beginning in the late 1800s CE, Human industrial activity gradually raised the average temperature of the planet. During the 21st century, the effects of Earth's climate change would be felt the hardest, causing Humanity to work towards mitigating and reversing global warming. By the mid 23rd century - just prior to Earth's destruction - large scale weather manipulation had been successful in bringing the global temperature closer to its historical average.</p><p>Approximately 71% of Earth's surface was covered in water, mainly in the form of salt water oceans. Earth had many large continents; which when combined with it's temperature range gave Earth a massive range of biomes and ecosystems. Earth's tropical, temperate, and polar climate zones were all largely equal in size to one another, meaning no single ecosystem dominated the planet. Earth sported large deserts in all three climate zones, as well as sizable ice caps in the polar regions.</p><h1>Native Flora and Fauna</h1>",
